When generating any UI component, screen, or styling code for the StyleOS app, follow these rules without deviation. These rules apply globally: every screen, card, button, and text element.

Typography

Two fonts only. Never introduce a third.

Primary font: Noto Serif

Use for all headings, titles, screen-level headlines, hero card names, section titles, and any large display text. Anywhere the user sees a "title", it is Noto Serif.

Examples of where Noto Serif is used:

- Screen titles ("Styled for you", "What's the occasion?", "Your look for today")
- Greeting headlines ("Good Morning, Snehal")
- Hero card names
- Section headers
- Large numerical displays
- Any prominent display text intended to feel editorial

Secondary font: Inter

Use for everything else: body text, supporting copy, captions, labels, button text, input field text, small metadata, navigation labels, chips, pills, form fields, and all functional UI text.

Examples of where Inter is used:

- All button text including primary CTAs ("Try this on me", "Add to cart", "Continue")
- Body copy and descriptions
- Field labels and input placeholders
- Search bar text
- Address bar text
- Filter pill labels ("Work", "Casual", "Date night")
- Match score chips ("91% your style")
- Delivery info ("Delivered by tomorrow")
- Card metadata (brand names, prices)
- Bottom nav labels
- Section subtitles and captions

Font implementation

When setting up the project, install both fonts using either Expo Google Fonts or react-native-fonts:

- @expo-google-fonts/noto-serif, or noto-serif from react-native-fonts
- @expo-google-fonts/inter

Define them in a typography theme file. Use Noto Serif via the family "NotoSerif_400Regular" or "NotoSerif_500Medium" for headings, and Inter via "Inter_400Regular" for CTAs and regular UI text. Use "Inter_500Medium" only for small emphasis where explicitly needed.

Never use the platform default font (System, San Francisco, Roboto). Always use Inter as the fallback for any UI text.

Type scale

Use this exact scale across the app. Do not invent new sizes.

- Display headline: Noto Serif, 500, 28px, line-height 1.2. Used once per screen for the main page title.
- H2: Noto Serif, 500, 24px, line-height 1.25. Used for secondary screen-level headings and form-step titles such as "What is your phone number?"
- Section heading: Noto Serif, 500, 22px, line-height 1.25. Used for section labels like "Styled for you" and "What's the occasion?"
- Card title: Noto Serif, 500, 16px, line-height 1.3. Used for product names and look names.
- Body large: Inter, 400, 14px, line-height 1.5. Primary body copy.
- Body: Inter, 400, 13px, line-height 1.5. Default UI text.
- Caption: Inter, 400, 12px, line-height 1.5. Supporting text and descriptions.
- Small caption: Inter, 400, 11px, line-height 1.4. Chip labels and metadata.

Never use bright accent colors. The app's design language is editorial and neutral. Color comes from the product photography itself, not from UI chrome.

Component conventions

- Primary button: filled black pill, white Inter 400 text, 44px height, 24px horizontal padding, 999px border-radius (full pill).
- Secondary button: transparent full-width pill with #D9D9D9 border, black Inter 400 text, 48px height, 24px horizontal padding, 999px border-radius (full pill). It should fill the same available parent width as the primary CTA unless a specific compact variant is requested.

Tone of voice in UI text

- Never use ALL CAPS except for legal/disclosure text.
- Never use exclamation points in UI copy.
- Use sentence case for buttons and labels: "Try this on me", not "TRY THIS ON ME" or "Try This On Me".
- Be conversational, not promotional: "Styled for you", not "Personalised picks!"
